Crate root for `ctx-scan`, a standalone tool that walks an arbitrary directory (not necessarily a git repo) and maintains a `.context/` tree of generated summaries, mirroring what `ctx-summarize` does for git-tracked file lists.

The file itself is just module wiring plus the crate-level doc comment — no logic. It re-exports `cli`, `contract`, `error`, `hash`, `readme`, `runner`, `walker` as public modules with no additional glue.

Key architectural facts stated in the doc comment, load-bearing for anyone editing this crate: prompt files are read at runtime from a configurable directory (default `prompts/` relative to process cwd) rather than embedded, so prompts are decoupled from the scanned tree. Change detection is content-hash based via the `hash` module — `--check` does staleness detection with zero model calls, `--update` regenerates only files whose hash changed. Programmatic entry points are `runner::scan_run`, `runner::check_run`, `runner::update_run`; CLI entry is `cli::dispatch`. Anyone adding a new subcommand or mode should wire it through both `cli::dispatch` and the corresponding `runner::*_run` function to keep the two surfaces in sync.